Document Structure:
<!DOCTYPE html>: Declares the document type and version of HTML being used.
<html>: The root element of an HTML page, enclosing all other HTML elements.
<head>: Contains metadata about the HTML document, such as the page title, links to stylesheets, and scripts.
<title>: Specifies the title of the HTML document, displayed in the browser tab or window title bar.
<body>: Contains the visible content of the HTML document, including text, images, links, and other elements.
Text Content:
<h1> to <h6>: Define headings of different levels, with <h1> being the most important and <h6> the least.
<p>: Defines a paragraph of text.
<a>: Creates a hyperlink, linking to another document or resource. The href attribute specifies the destination URL.
<img>: Embeds an image into the document. The src attribute specifies the image file path, and alt provides alternative text for accessibility.
<ul>: Defines an unordered (bulleted) list.
<ol>: Defines an ordered (numbered) list.
<li>: Defines a list item within <ul> or <ol>.
<strong>: Indicates strong importance or emphasis, typically displayed as bold text.
<em>: Indicates emphasis, typically displayed as italic text.
<span>: A generic inline container for phrasing content, used for styling or scripting specific parts of text.
<div>: A generic block-level container, used for grouping and styling larger sections of content.
Forms:
<form>: Creates an HTML form for user input.
<input>: Creates various interactive controls for forms, such as text fields, checkboxes, and radio buttons.
<button>: Creates a clickable button.
<select>: Creates a dropdown list for selecting options.
Other Common Tags:
<br>: Inserts a line break.
<hr>: Creates a horizontal rule, often used to separate content visually.
<header>: Represents introductory content or a set of navigational links for a section or the entire document.
<footer>: Represents a footer for its nearest sectioning content or the nearest root element.
<nav>: Represents a section of navigation links.
<article>: Represents a self-contained composition in a document, page, application, or site.
<section>: Represents a standalone section of a document.